thoughts.a: The input grid and output grids are the same sizes. The input grid has a black colored background and a single gray bounding box square, with the interior fully black color background. The output grid has this exact gray bounding box in the same location, but now with additional colored bounding boxes inside of it. The layers go in the following pattern: red, gray, and then background color black. Then gray, red, and presumably another gray layer but there were no more interior layers to color at that point, and the pattern terminated at the 2x2 red square. Thus the hypothesis is the following. Input grid will have a black color background and a gray bounding box located somewhere in it. In order to construct the output grid, we need to layer the interior of this gray bounding box with a pattern. That pattern is dictated by the following gray, red, gray, and then a black background color. The original gray layer is the starting layer of this gray red gray pattern. After the black color background layer, the pattern of gray red gray will presumably repeat. However, since this starting bounding box wasn't large enough, I would like additional training pairs to confirm this hypothesis.
thoughts.b: The input and output grids are again the same sizes. The input grid has a black color background with a gray bounding box. In this case, that gray bounding box happens to be the entire edge of the input grid, but that's still allowed by the hypothesis. According to the hypothesis, we identify the gray bounding box as a starting pattern of layers of bounding boxes in the form of gray red gray and then black background color, which is then repeated until all the interior has been applied with that rule. In this case, we only get one layer of red on the interior and another layer of gray and the pattern terminates because we are at the 2x2 tile center of the original gray bounding box. Because this is exactly what we see in the output grid the hypothesis holds.

The pattern goes like a gray, red, gray, and then black color background and repeated until we can no longer color new layers because we've hit the center parts of the bounding box. In this case, we have enough space to have two full sets of gray, red, gray, black, with the very center single tile being the start of the next instance of the full pattern, which means the very center would be a single gray tile. Because this is what we find in the output grid the hypothesis holds.

thoughts.e: We apply the hypothesis here. The input and output grids are the same sizes. Input grid is a black color background with a single gray bounding box in it. According to the hypothesis, we identified this gray bounding box as the starting layer of a pattern of layers of bounding boxes that need to be drawn in the output grid in the interior. The pattern goes like gray, red, gray, and then the black color background. there's enough space interior of this starting gray bounding box then this pattern repeats until we can no longer color new layers because we've hit the center parts of the interior. In this case, the input grid's original gray bounding box is large enough to have have three instances of the full rotation of colors in the pattern. That is, we will have one instance of gray, red, gray, black, and then another full instance of gray, red, gray, black. And then yet another full instance of gray, red, gray, and black. We know this because the bounding box is 25 tiles wide, and each instance of the full pattern takes up 8 total layers.
